PwnLab

Target IP: 192.168.186.29

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP, RPC, MySQL, and another RPC.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


Performing a directory search leads to the result above. There are some interesting pages like the config.php and upload.php.


This application displays the webpage above. I find the parameter page interesting as it is used to include a page in the webpage.



When performing normal LFI, it will not work. However, I notice the config.php. Maybe I can obtain that file using php-filter? And it worked. By sending the payload php://filter/convert.base64-encode/resource=config I obtained the configuration files for the MySQL database.

Port 3306: MySQL

I used the command mysql -u root -h 192.168.186.29 -p to connect to the MySQL application using the credentials I obtained from the LFI using PHP filter. There is a database called Users. This database contains a table called users. The contents of this table are shown above. The passwords are in base64 format.


After decoding each base64 string, I obtained their original format. Now if the usernames and passwords work, I should be able to gain access to the login page.

Exploitation


Looks like another LFI vulnerability is here. I can use the lang parameter to perform LFI.



By replacing the PHPSESSID parameter with lang for Cookie:, it is possible to perform LFI!



The web application does not allow php to be uploaded, so there is a filtering in place. Using the PHP filter, I should be able to retrieve the upload.php file to identify what filtering is in action. I successfully retrieved the file in base64 format.


After running the base64 string in a decoder, I obtained the result above. It looks like there is an extensive amount of filtering in place.


The highlighted areas in the picture above shows what parameters were changed to bypass the filter. I used PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script. I should be able to use the first LFI vulnerability inside cookie to gain a reverse shell connection.

Privilege Escalation


Using the password I obtained from the database, I switched to kane and found an interesting execution file called msgmike. In the screenshot above, cat is called without absolute path!



I took advantage of this PATH vulnerability.


There is another interesting binary called msg2root. Using strings on this binary shows it calls /bin/echo on it.


Then spawning a root shell is possible by entering a message followed by /bin/sh. I tried /bin/bash first, and it did not work. But now I have a root shell.
